        "name": "Security for Cannabis related business?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Since the sale of Cannabis is still illegal at the Federal level there are no Federal guidelines concerning the level of security you must have.
Since cannabis legalization has been enacted at a state level, state cannabis security regulations do exist. Most States have extensive guidelines that are similar to Federal requirements for the storage and sale of prescription drugs. It is also important to remember that this is currently a strictly cash business and as such raises additional security concerns. As each State is different you will have to do further research to determine exactly what requirements are needed.
Below are some of the most common requirements, but again these are just a general guide and are not to be relied upon as what your business needs:
You must take calculated measures to deter and prevent unauthorized entrance into areas containing marijuana. This includes who has access to the building.
In order to apply for marijuana licensing, you will need to provide a documented security plan.
If there is a loss, theft or breech of the premises the regulatory agency of the State must be notified, usually within a specified time frame.
Licensed premises must have a video surveillance system. They need to be of high quality and have coverage of all areas of the premises where product is stored or available. There also needs to be sufficient storage of the recorded images as well, such as a high capacity NVR (network video recorder).
There needs to be a safe room where inventory is stored that meets the State guidelines.
Storefront businesses typically require security personnel during at least the hours of operation, and, in some circumstances, 24/7.
There must be an alarm system that has central monitoring.
It is important to remember that these security measures also offer you and you employees protection from robbery, so it is important to take this seriously.
